\cf1\f0\fs32 [How to Customize These Skins - Settings.txt]\cf2\f1\fs22\par
     Elementary's settings/user preferences are in the file "\b\i ...\\Skins\\Elementary\\@Resources\\Settings.txt\b0\i0 "; open this file in any text editor to change your preferences.  You can also right click an Elementary skin, and in the context menu select "Elementary > Settings.ini" to quickly open the file in Windows Notepad.\par
     The settings are given in Key=Value pairs; to change a setting, modify the portion after the "=" sign, save the file, and refresh any open Elementary skins.\par
\b\f2 font\b0 ,\b  font2\b0\f1  - the primary and secondary fonts used by the skins.  You can use any installed font, just know that the positions of the skin elements are optimized for the two default fonts.  Changing fonts \i will\i0  throw off positioning and you will have to edit the skin .inis to alter that.\par
\b\f2 color\b0\f1  - the color of the skins, given in Decimal or Hexadecimal format.  The default is 255,255,255,180; for a dark skins, try 0,0,0,200 and play around with it from there.  (See the "Helpful Links and Tools" section for a link to more information on color codes in Rainmeter.)\par
\b\f2 style\b0\f1  - sets the attributes of the text in the skins.  Valid values are "NORMAL," BOLD," "ITALIC," and "BOLDITALIC."\par
\b\f2 scalar\b0\f1  - modifies the size of the anolog clock.  Use a larger number to increase the size, or a smaller number to decrease it.  I would recommend staying between 1.5 and 5.0.\par
\b\f2 woeid\f1  - \b0 the Yahoo! WOEID location code for the Weather skin.  You can find your WOEID here:\par
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://woeid.rosselliot.co.nz/lookup/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul\cf3 http://woeid.rosselliot.co.nz/lookup/}}}\f1\fs22\par
\b\f2 unit\b0\f1  - sets the units used in the Weather skin.  Valid values are \b f\b0  (English) or \b c\b0  (Metric).\par
\b\f2 language\b0\f1  - the two letter ISO 639-1 code for your preferred language.  Languages currently included are: \par
\pard{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl276\slmult1 English (\b en\b0 , the default) \par
\pard\sl276\slmult1 See the next section ("Creating your own Translation file") for instructions on translating the skins to whatever language you would like.\par
\b\f2 drive\b0\f1  - the hard drive you wish to monitor with the system skin.\par
\b\f2 hour\b0\f1  - is the format code for the Hour in the time skins.  For 12 hour format, use "\b %#I\b0 "; for 24 hour format, use "\b %#H\b0 ".  To add leading zeros, remove the "#" sign (i.e., %I instead of %#I will give you "08" instead of "8").\par
\b\f2 player\b0\f1  - Music player for the NowPlaying skin.  List of supported options is in the documentation for the NowPlaying plugin: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://docs.rainmeter.net/manual/plugins/nowplaying#playerlist"}}{\fldrslt{\ul\cf3 http://docs.rainmeter.net/manual/plugins/nowplaying#playerlist}}}\f1\fs22\par
\par
\cf1\f0\fs32 [Creating Your Own Translation File - template.txt]\cf2\par
\f1\fs22 To make your own custom translation file to use with Elementary, look in "\b\i ...\\Skins\\Elementary\\@Resources\\Languages\\\b0\i0 "\b\i  \b0\i0 for the file "\i template.txt\i0 ".  This file lists all "keys" for the skins with no "values" (translations).\par
To make a new translation file: \par
\pard{\pntext\f1 1.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf1\pnindent0\pnstart1\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\fi-360\li720\sl276\slmult1 Make a copy of the template file, naming the new copy something appropriate for your language.  (I suggest the ISO 639-1 code, because it is simple, universal, and will fit with the "official" translations.)  \par
{\pntext\f1 2.\tab}Open your new copy and fill in all the values after the '=' signs with the appropriate word or phrase in your language.  Save your changes.\par
{\pntext\f1 3.\tab}In Settings.txt, set "language" to whatever you named your new translation file (without the .txt extension).  Save Settings.txt and refresh any open Elementary skins.  The skins should now use your new translations.\par
\pard\sl276\slmult1 You can check the translation files already included in the "...\\@Resources\\Languages\\" folder for examples.\par
\b\i Some notes:\b0\i0\par
\pard{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl276\slmult1 The default fonts might not support the special characters in some languages.  In such cases you will need to change the font to one that includes the correct characters.\par
{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}Translation files with special characters should be encoded with Unicode.  You can read more specifics here: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://docs.rainmeter.net/tips/unicode-in-rainmeter"}}{\fldrslt{\ul\cf3 http://docs.rainmeter.net/tips/unicode-in-rainmeter}}}\f1\fs22  (see the section "Using Unicode in Rainmeter" for how to save the file in a particular text editor).\par
{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}If a word in your language is much longer than that word/phrase in English, then there may be some problems with text being cut-off in some of the skins.  This should be easily solved with a minor positioning tweak in that skin's .ini file, but consider using shorter synonyms if possible to make it easier to redistribute your translation.\par
\pard\sl276\slmult1\b\i If you would like to have your translation added to the official Elementary distribution:\b0\i0\par
\pard{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl276\slmult1 Email me (see the "Contact the Author" section below).  Just attach your new translation's .txt file, and be sure to indicate how you would like to be credited (real name or username, the URL for your web site or DeviantArt page, that sort of thing).\par
{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}Send a Pull Request on GitHub.  Feel free to fork the Elementary repository on GitHub, add your translation file, and send a pull request so I can merge your translation into the main repo.  \i This is the preferred method \i0 as it makes it much easier for me to keep track of the files and who did what (that's why they call it Version Control!)\par
\pard\sl276\slmult1\par
